<div class="donationdrive">
<a id="donations">
<h2>Donation & Update Schedule</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Cumulative donations</th><th>Update schedule</th></tr>
<tr><td>$0</td><td>Monthly Prudence update</td></tr>
<tr><td>$100</td><td>Weekly Prudence updates</td></tr>
<tr><td>$200</td><td>Weekly Prudence update, plus one update of another story</td></tr>
<tr><td>$300</td><td>Weekly Prudence update, plus two other updates/week</td></tr>
<tr><td>$400</td><td>Weekly Prudence update, plus three other updates/week</td></tr>
<tr><td>$500</td><td>Weekly Prudence update, plus four other updates/week</td></tr>
<tr><td>$600</td><td>Weekly Prudence update, plus five other updates/week</td></tr>
<tr><td>$700</td><td>Weekly Prudence update, plus six other updates/week</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Let me start with this: The donation drive is <em>not</em> meant to be any sort of demand or extortion. Everything we put out as a result of donations _will_ be put out no matter what; all the donations affect is <em>when</em> things come out, and the schedule above is a <em>minimum</em>. We'll try for monthly updates of all the stories we've started, no matter what we get in donations, but the only one we guarantee is Prudence (because I, at least, am unfortunately rather prone to procrastination).</p>
<p>I'm not going to try to convince people to donate; in fact, I'm going to do just the <em>opposite</em>. If you don't think the work is high enough quality that it deserves it, or if you don't care when things come out, <strong>DON'T DONATE</strong>.</p>
<p>Donate if you like the stories that much. Donate if you can't wait to find out what comes next, and you don't want to wait a month between updates. <em>Those</em> are the reasons to update.</p>
<p>Right now, the default story for the second weekly update is Prudence. If that's <em>not</em> what you want, or if there's a particular story you want moved to the head of the queue, <em>let us know</em>. We have <a href="#contact">email addresses</a>. We have the <a href="http://playground.pele.cx/forums">forums</a>. We <em>want</em> to know what you think, and from day one we've said that we'd choose what stories went up based on your votes.</p>
<p>So far, we've gotten almost no votes that don't boil down to "I like all of it, so whatever you want to put up is fine with me". Well, we're glad you feel that way! It's nice to know that people think all the stories are good. But that doesn't help us figure out what to post, which is why it's been Prudence and Pandora the last month and a half.</p>
<p>And <strong>you don't have to donate to vote</strong>, either. Admittedly, if things are close, we'll go with what the donors want -- that's just common sense. But you don't have to donate to email us. And you don't have to donate to join the forums and let us know what you think. We <em>want</em> your feedback.</p>
<p>In fact, in a very real way we want your feedback <em>more</em> if you don't donate -- we want to know how we could improve the stories. Not that I'm saying we're going to change what we write based on popular opinion; if we were going to do that, Aaron would never have become part of the Prudence family, because we did that knowing we'd probably lose a lot of readers (though, to be fair, that hasn't happened <em>nearly</em> as much as we'd expected). But we <em>do</em> listen to what people have to say; if several people say that a certain scene didn't work for them, we're going to look at <em>why</em> that was and try to do it right the next time.</p>
<p>It all comes down to this: we want you to donate what you think the work is worth. If that's nothing, then that's what we want you to donate.</p>
<p>If people don't want Prudence to be at the head of the queue, tell us. Remember that, the second weekly update defaults to Prudence; the few votes we've gotten said Prudence (and several asked for a third or fourth Prudence update!), so that's what it's been. It doesn't _have_ to be (but you'll have to outvote the Prudence lovers!).</p>
<p>Also, note -- money in excess of a breakpoint (IE, the $50 in $350) will be applied to the next month's donations, giving it a head start.</p>
